t-happens-during-the-motorcycle-practical-test","order":3,"title":"What happens during the motorcycle practical test","body":"<p>The practical motorcycle test is split into 2 separate modules - the <strong>off-road module</strong> and the <strong>on-road module</strong>. To get a full motorcycle licence you need to pass both modules.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can book both modules at the same time, but you must pass module 1 before you take module 2.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t pass module 1, you must wait 3 full working days before you can retake it.</p>\n\n<h2>Cancelling module 2</h2>\n\n<p>You have to give 3 full working days&rsquo; notice to cancel your module 2 test. Otherwise you’ll lose your module 2 test fee.</p>\n\n<p>You should leave a long enough time between the 2 modules so you don’t lose the module 2 fee if you don’t pass module 1 first time.</p>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t pass module 2, you have to wait 10 full working days before you can take it again.</p>\n\n<h2>Reporting for your riding test modules</h2>\n\n<p>You need to bring <a href=\"/motorcycle-practical-test/documents-you-need-to-take-to-your-test\" title=\"certain documents\">certain documents</a> with you and a <a href=\"/motorcycle-practical-test/rules-for-mopeds-and-motorcycles-used-in-the-practical-riding-test\" title=\"suitable moped or motorcycle\">suitable moped or motorcycle</a>.</p>\n\n<h3>Clothing rules</h3>\n\n<p>You should wear appropriate motorcycle clothing to your test.</p>\n\n<p>If you don’t wear the right clothing for your test it might be cancelled and you could lose your fee.</p>\n\n<h2>Module 1: off-road manoeuvres</h2>\n\n<p>Module 1 is the off-road module and normally takes about 20 minutes.</p>\n\n<p>It includes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>wheeling the moped or motorcycle and using the stand</li>\n  <li>riding a slalom and figure of 8</li>\n  <li>a slow ride</li>\n  <li>a U-turn</li>\n  <li>cornering and controlled stop</li>\n  <li>cornering and the emergency stop</li>\n  <li>cornering and hazard avoidance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>There is a minimum speed for the hazard avoidance and emergency stop exercises:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>for mopeds this is around 19mph</li>\n  <li>for motorcycles this is around 31mph</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Motorcycle manoeuvring area</h3>\n\n<p>Module 1 takes place in a safe off-road area called a motorcycle manoeuvring area. The layout of the area depends on where you take your test.</p>\n\n<p>You can download diagrams showing the different types of layout.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_197120.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘Motorcycle manoeuvring - DSA multi-purpose test centre’ (PDF,622KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Motorcycle manoeuvring - <abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr> multi-purpose test centre’ (PDF, 622KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_197118.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘Motorcycle manoeuvring - avoidance to left’ (PDF, 104KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Motorcycle manoeuvring - avoidance to left’ (PDF, 104KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_197119.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘Motorcycle manoeuvring - avoidance to right’ (PDF, 114KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Motorcycle manoeuvring - avoidance to right’ (PDF, 114KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Module 2: on-road riding</h2>\n\n<p>Module 2 is the on-road module and normally takes about 40 minutes.</p>\n\n<p>You must bring your module 1 pass certificate to module 2, plus all the documents you had to bring to the module 1 test.</p>\n\n<h2>What happens during module 2</h2>\n\n<p>Module 2 includes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>eyesight test</li>\n  <li>safety and balance questions</li>\n  <li>road riding</li>\n  <li>independent riding</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>The eyesight test</h3>\n\n<p>You’ll have to correctly read a number plate on a parked vehicle.</p>\n\n<p>The vehicle will be at least 20 metres away if it has a new-style number plate, and 20.5 metres away if it has an old-style number plate.</p>\n\n<p>New-style number plates start with 2 letters followed by 2 numbers, for example AB51 ABC.</p>\n\n<p>If you can’t pass the eyesight test you’ll fail your test and the test won&rsquo;t continue.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you can’t speak English or have difficulty reading, you can write down what you see.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Vehicle safety and balance questions</h3>\n\n<p>You can download a list of all the safety and balance questions you could be asked by the examiner.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_197378.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘Vehicle safety questions for motorcycle tests’ (PDF, 15KB)\">Download ‘Vehicle safety questions for motorcycle tests’ (PDF, 15KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Road riding</h3>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll ride in a variety of road and traffic conditions. You&rsquo;ll be asked to carry out:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>normal stops</li>\n  <li>an angle start (pulling out from behind a parked vehicle)</li>\n  <li>a hill start (where possible)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The examiner will give you directions using a radio. They will normally follow you on a motorcycle.</p>\n\n<h3>Independent riding</h3>\n\n<p>You’ll have about 10 minutes of <a href=\"/motorcycle-practical-test/independent-riding-section-of-the-test\" title=\"independent riding\">independent riding</a>. This is designed to assess your ability to ride safely while making your own decisions.</p>\n\n<h3>At the end of module 2</h3>\n\n<p>At the end of module 2, the examiner will give you the result and feedback. If you pass, the examiner will explain to you how to change your provisional licence into a full licence.</p>\n\n<h2>Your riding test result</h2>\n\n<p>At the end of each module the examiner will tell you if you’ve passed or not and give you feedback on your riding.</p>\n\n<p>When you pass module 1, you’ll get your module 1 pass certificate which you&rsquo;ll need when you take module 2.</p>\n\n<p>When you pass module 2, you&rsquo;ll be told how to <a href=\"/claiming-driving-test-pass\" title=\"claim your driving test pass\">claim your test pass</a> and get your full licence.</p>\n\n<h3>Types of faults</h3>\n\n<p>There are 3 types of faults that can be marked:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a dangerous fault - involves actual danger to you, the examiner, the public or property</li>\n  <li>a serious fault - could potentially be dangerous</li>\n  <li>a rider fault - not potentially dangerous, but if you make the same fault throughout your test it could become a serious fault</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Module 1 pass mark</h3>\n\n<p>You need to make 5 or fewer rider faults to pass module 1.</p>\n\n<p>You’ll automatically fail if you make 1 serious or dangerous fault.</p>\n\n<h3>Module 2 pass mark</h3>\n\n<p>You need to make 10 or fewer rider faults to pass module 2.</p>\n\n<p>You’ll automatically fail if you make 1 serious or dangerous fault.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/independent-riding-section-of-the-test","slug":"independent-riding-section-of-the-test","order":4,"title":"Independent riding section of the test","body":"<p>Your practical motorcycle test will include approximately 10 minutes of independent riding. It&rsquo;s not a test of your orientation and navigation skills.</p>\n\n<h2>How the test works</h2>\n\n<p>During your test you&rsquo;ll have to ride independently by either following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>traffic signs</li>\n  <li>a series of directions</li>\n  <li>a combination of both</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>To help you understand where you are going when following verbal directions, the examiner will show you a diagram.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can’t use sat nav because the independent riding section tests how you make your own decisions.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>If you forget the directions</h3>\n\n<p>It doesn&rsquo;t matter if you don&rsquo;t remember every direction, or if you go the wrong way - that can happen to the most experienced riders.</p>\n\n<p>Independent riding is not a test of your orientation and navigation skills. Riding independently means making your own decisions - this includes deciding when it&rsquo;s safe and appropriate to ask for confirmation about where you&rsquo;re going.</p>\n\n<p>If you ask for a reminder of the directions, the examiner will confirm them to you.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_196536.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘Independent driving route diagram example’ (PDF, 315KB)\">Download ‘Independent driving route diagram example’ (PDF, 315KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>If you go off the independent riding route</h3>\n\n<p>If you go off the independent riding route it won&rsquo;t affect the result of your test unless you make a riding fault.</p>\n\n<p>If you go off the route or take a wrong turning, the examiner will help you get back on the route. You can then continue with the independent riding.</p>\n\n<h3>If there are poor traffic signs</h3>\n\n<p>If there are poor or obscured traffic signs, the examiner will give you directions until you can see the next traffic sign. You won&rsquo;t need to have a detailed knowledge of the area.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/your-test-result","slug":"your-test-result","order":5,"title":"Your test result","body":"<p>You&rsquo;ll pass your test if you make:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>5 or less riding faults on module 1</li>\n  <li>10 or less riding faults on module 2</li>\n  <li>no serious or dangerous faults</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>When the test has ended, you can call your instructor over. This is so they can listen to the result and help you with any feedback afterwards.</p>\n\n<p>The examiner will:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>tell you if you passed or not</li>\n  <li>explain how you did during the test</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>The different types of faults</h2>\n\n<p>There are 3 types of faults that can be marked:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a dangerous fault - involves actual danger to you, the examiner, the public or property</li>\n  <li>a serious fault - could potentially be dangerous</li>\n  <li>a driving fault - not potentially dangerous, but if you make the same fault throughout your test it could become a serious fault</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>If you pass your test</h2>\n\n<p>If you pass your test the examiner will give you a pass certificate. They will also ask you if you want your full licence to be sent to you automatically.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Once you have passed your test you can start riding straight away - you don’t need to wait for your full licence to arrive.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you don’t pass</h2>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t pass, you have to wait another 10 working days before you can take another test. Working days include Saturdays.</p>\n\n<h2>Feedback on how eco-efficient your riding is</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner will also give you feedback about how eco-efficient your riding is.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/motorcycle-practical-test-fees-","slug":"motorcycle-practical-test-fees-","order":6,"title":"Motorcycle practical test fees ","body":"\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>The Driving Standards Agency (<abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>) recommends that all learner riders book their practical test through the <a href=\"/book-practical-driving-test\" title=\"official booking service\">official booking service</a>. There is no administration fee. Unofficial booking websites may charge a fee.</p>\n</div>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Practical test type</th>\n      <th>Weekday price</th>\n      <th>Weekday evening, weekend and bank holiday price</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Motorcycle: module 1 (off-road)</td>\n      <td>£15.50</td>\n      <td>£15.50</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>Motorcycle: module 2 (on-road)</td>\n      <td>£75</td>\n      <td>£88.50</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h2>Retests</h2>\n\n<p>If you don’t pass your practical test, and want to take another one, you’ll have to pay the full amount again.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/rules-for-mopeds-and-motorcycles-used-in-the-practical-riding-test","slug":"rules-for-mopeds-and-motorcycles-used-in-the-practical-riding-test","order":7,"title":"Rules for mopeds and motorcycles used in the practical riding test","body":"<p>There are rules about the moped or motorcycle you use for your riding test.</p>\n\n<p>If your vehicle does not meet the rules, you can&rsquo;t use it for your test - <strong>your test will be cancelled and you may lose your fee</strong>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>The rules are changing. If you’re taking a test from 19 January 2013 onwards you’ll need to follow <a href=\"/motorcycle-practical-test/new-rules-for-mopeds-and-motorcycles-from-19-january-2013\" title=\"new rules for mopeds and motorcycles\">the new rules</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Rules for mopeds</h2>\n\n<p>The moped you use for your test must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be no more than 50cc</li>\n  <li>have a top speed of no more than around 31mph</li>\n  <li>have a speedometer measuring speed in mph</li>\n  <li>display L plates (&lsquo;L&rsquo; or &lsquo;D&rsquo; plates in Wales) on the front and rear</li>\n  <li>be insured, taxed and roadworthy and have no engine warning lights showing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Rules for motorcycles</h2>\n\n<p>The motorcycle you use for your test must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be 75cc or more</li>\n  <li>have a speedometer measuring speed in mph</li>\n  <li>display L plates (&lsquo;L&rsquo; or &lsquo;D&rsquo; plates in Wales) on the front and rear</li>\n  <li>be insured, taxed and roadworthy and have no engine warning lights showing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You can’t use enclosed motorcycles like the BMW C1 for the test.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Automatic and semi-automatic motorcycles</h3>\n\n<p>If you pass your test on a motorcycle with automatic or semi-automatic transmission you’ll only get a full licence for those types of motorcycle.</p>\n\n<h2>Motorcycle sub-categories</h2>\n\n<p>There are 3 sub-categories of motorcycles you can use for your test. The sub-category of motorcycle you use affects the sub-categories you can ride after passing your test.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You must use the same sub-category of motorcycle for both modules of the test.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Sub-category A1 (light motorcycle)</h3>\n\n<p>A sub-category A1 motorcycle is a solo motorcycle between 75 and 125cc.</p>\n\n<p>They have a power output of no more than 11kW</p>\n\n<p>If you pass your test on a motorcycle in this sub-category you’ll get a licence to ride motorcycles up to 125cc.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://assets.dft.gov.uk/dsa-bl/dsa-motorcycle-mtv.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘List of A1 and A2 motorcycles’ (PDF, 21KB)\">Download ‘List of A1 and A2 motorcycles’ (PDF, 21KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Sub-category A2 (standard motorcycle)</h3>\n\n<p>A sub-category A2 motorcycle is a solo motorcycle between 121 and 125cc.</p>\n\n<p>They must be able to go faster than 62mph.</p>\n\n<p>If you pass your test on a motorcycle in this sub-category of motorcycle you can ride motorcycles with a power output of no more than 25kW.</p>\n\n<p>This restriction lasts for 2 years and then you can ride a motorcycle of any engine size and power output.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://assets.dft.gov.uk/dsa-bl/dsa-motorcycle-mtv.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘List of A1 and A2 motorcycles’ (PDF, 21KB)\">Download ‘List of A1 and A2 motorcycles’ (PDF, 21KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Category A (unrestricted)</h3>\n\n<p>A category A unrestricted motorcycle is a solo motorcycle with a power output of at least 35kW.</p>\n\n<p>If you pass your test on an unrestricted motorcycle, you can ride a motorcycle of any engine size and power output.</p>\n\n<p>You can take your test on an unrestricted motorcycle under the direct access scheme or accelerated access scheme.</p>\n\n<h2>Rules for motorcycles with sidecars</h2>\n\n<p>You can only use a motorcycle with a sidecar for your test if you have special needs affecting balance or any loss of a limb meaning it&rsquo;s impractical to ride a solo machine.</p>\n\n<p>The rules for a motorcycle with a sidecar are the same as for a solo motorcycle, but:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>category A and sub-category A1 can’t have a power to weight ratio of more than 0.16kW/kg</li>\n  <li>passengers are not allowed to ride in the sidecar during the test</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you pass your test in a motorcycle with sidecar your licence will only be for motorcycles with sidecars.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/new-rules-for-mopeds-and-motorcycles-from-19-january-2013","slug":"new-rules-for-mopeds-and-motorcycles-from-19-january-2013","order":8,"title":"New rules for mopeds and motorcycles from 19 January 2013","body":"<p>The rules about the moped or motorcycle you use for your riding test are changing.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re planning to take your test from 19 January 2013 you&rsquo;ll need to make sure your vehicle meets the new rules.</p>\n\n<p>Otherwise your test will be cancelled and you may lose your fee.</p>\n\n<h2>Rules for mopeds</h2>\n\n<p>The moped you use for your test from 19 January 2013 must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be a solo machine</li>\n  <li>be no more than 50cc</li>\n  <li>have a top speed of no more than 28mph</li>\n  <li>have a speedometer measuring speed in mph</li>\n  <li>display L plates (‘L’ or ‘D’ plates in Wales) on the front and rear</li>\n  <li>be insured, taxed and roadworthy and have no engine warning lights showing</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Rules for all motorcycles</h2>\n\n<p>The motorcycle you use for your test must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>have a speedometer measuring speed in mph</li>\n  <li>display L plates (‘L’ or ‘D’ plates in Wales) on the front and rear</li>\n  <li>be insured, taxed and roadworthy and have no engine warning lights showing</li>\n  <li>be suitable for the test you&rsquo;re taking</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://assets.dft.gov.uk/dsa-bl/dsa-motorcycle-mtv-jan13.pdf\" title=\"Download ‘List of motorcycles for test from 19 January 2013' (PDF, 13KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘List of motorcycles for test from 19 January 2013’ (PDF, 13KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Automatic and semi-automatic motorcycles</h3>\n\n<p>If you pass your test on a motorcycle with automatic or semi-automatic transmission you’ll only get a full licence for those types of motorcycle.</p>\n\n<h2>Age restrictions</h2>\n\n<p>From 19 January 2013 there&rsquo;ll be new age restrictions on the category of motorcycle you can use to take your  test.</p>\n\n<p>The table below shows what sub-category you&rsquo;ll need to use for module 2 if you&rsquo;ve already passed module 1 before 19 January 2013.</p>\n\n<table>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Your age from 19 January 2013</th>\n      <th>Sub-category used for module 1 before 19 January 2013</th>\n      <th>Sub-category used for module 2 after 19 January 2013</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td>16 or over</td>\n      <td>P</td>\n      <td>AM</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>17 or over</td>\n      <td>A1</td>\n      <td>A1</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>17 or over</td>\n      <td>A2</td>\n      <td>A1</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>23 or under</td>\n      <td>A</td>\n      <td>A2</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td>24 or over</td>\n      <td>A</td>\n      <td>A</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Your licence is only valid for the sub-category of motorcycle you pass your module 2 test on.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Motorcycle sub-categories</h2>\n\n<p>There are 3 sub-categories of motorcycles you can use for your test. The sub-category of motorcycle you use affects the sub-categories you can ride after passing your test.</p>\n\n<p>You must use the same sub-category of motorcycle for both modules of the test.</p>\n\n<h3>Sub-category A1 (light motorcycle)</h3>\n\n<p>Sub-category A1 motorcycles used for tests from 19 January 2013 must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be a solo motorcycle</li>\n  <li>be between 120cc and 125cc</li>\n  <li>be no more than 11kW engine power</li>\n  <li>be capable of at least 55mph</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Sub-category A2 (standard motorcycle)</h3>\n\n<p>Sub-category A2 motorcycles used for tests from 19 January 2013 must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be a solo motorcycle</li>\n  <li>be at least 395cc</li>\n  <li>be between 25kW and 35kW engine power</li>\n  <li>have a power to weight ratio no more than 0.2kW/kg</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the engine power of the motorcycle has been restricted to fit sub-category A2, the normal unrestricted power can’t be more than double its new restricted power.</p>\n\n<p>If you have an A2 restricted motorcycle, you must bring proof of the restriction to your test, or it will be cancelled. It must be on headed notepaper from a main dealer, official importer or recognised specialist, and must show the motorcycle&rsquo;s registration number.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>A dyno test certificate will not be accepted as proof of the restriction.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"example\">\n<p><strong>Example</strong><br />\nIf the original unrestricted power of your motorcycle was 60kW, you can&rsquo;t restrict it to less than 30kW.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Category A (unrestricted)</h3>\n\n<p>Category A unrestricted motorcycles used for tests from 19 January 2013 must:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>be a solo motorcycle</li>\n  <li>be at least 595cc</li>\n  <li>be at least 40kW engine power</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Rules for motorcycles with sidecars</h2>\n\n<p>You can only use a motorcycle with a sidecar for your test if you have certain disabilities.</p>\n\n<p>The rules for a motorcycle with a sidecar are the same as for a solo motorcycle, but:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>categories A and A1 can&rsquo;t have a power to weight ratio of more than 0.16kW/kg</li>\n  <li>passengers are not allowed to ride in the sidecar during the test</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If you pass your test in a motorcycle with sidecar your licence will only be for motorcycles with sidecars.</p>\n\n<h2>Motorcycles with variable power modes</h2>\n\n<p>It must be clear what power mode any switchable engine control unit (ECU) or variable power device is set to. If you are using one of these, your motorcycle cannot have:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>interchangeable carburrettor heads </li>\n  <li>an exhaust manifold restrictor </li>\n  <li>a hidden ECU</li>\n</ul>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/special-needs","slug":"special-needs","order":9,"title":"Special needs","body":"<p>When you book your practical test you should say if you have any special needs or disabilities.</p>\n\n<p>There are a number of facilities to help. You still take the same test as everyone else, no matter how serious your disability is. </p>\n\n<h2>Booking your practical test</h2>\n\n<p>When you book your test you&rsquo;ll be asked if you’ll be bringing an interpreter with you.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll also be asked if you have:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>any condition which affects your movement</li>\n  <li>any missing limbs</li>\n  <li>any special learning needs</li>\n  <li>arthritis</li>\n  <li>dyslexia</li>\n  <li>epilepsy</li>\n  <li>paraplegia</li>\n  <li>any other special needs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll also be asked if you’re:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>deaf - either profoundly or not</li>\n  <li>heavily pregnant</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Getting more time to take your test</h2>\n\n<p>More time might be allowed for your test if you have certain special needs. It will give the examiner time to talk to you about your disability and any adaptations fitted to your vehicle.</p>\n\n<h2>If English isn&rsquo;t your first language</h2>\n\n<p>You can bring your own interpreter for your practical test. They must be at least 16 years old. Your motorcycle trainer can be your interpreter.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need to arrange your own interpreter and pay any fees that they charge.</p>\n\n<h2>If you have hearing difficulties</h2>\n\n<p>If you are deaf or have hearing difficulties, at the start of the test the examiner will tell you what will happen by using written notes. They will also look at you to help you lip read what they are saying if you find that helpful.</p>\n\n<p>The examiner will agree with you the best way to communicate before your test starts.</p>\n\n<h3>Taking an interpreter with you</h3>\n\n<p>You can bring your own interpreter for your practical test if you use sign language.</p>\n\n<p>They must be at least 16 years old. Your motorcycle trainer can be your interpreter.</p>\n\n<p>You will need to arrange your own interpreter and pay any fees that they charge.</p>\n\n<h2>If you are pregnant</h2>\n\n<p>You can take a practical test at any stage of your pregnancy. However, you must be able and willing to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>do an emergency stop</li>\n  <li>manually handle and wheel the motorcycle</li>\n  <li>do the cornering and hazard avoidance exercise</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Taking the eyesight test if you have reading difficulties</h2>\n\n<p>At the start of the practical test, you will have an <a href=\"/driving-eyesight-rules\" title=\"eyesight test\">eyesight test</a>. The examiner will ask you to read the number plate on a parked vehicle.</p>\n\n<p>If you have learning difficulties or do not speak English, you can write down what you see on the number plate.</p>\n\n<h2>The independent riding section of the test</h2>\n\n<p>If you said you have special needs when you booked your test your examiner will know what kinds of reasonable adjustments to make for the <a href=\"/motorcycle-practical-test/independent-riding-section-of-the-test\" title=\"independent riding\">independent riding</a> part of your test. </p>\n\n<p>They might ask if you would prefer to follow traffic signs.</p>\n\n<p>You might be able to choose to follow a set of directions, supported by a diagram. In this case there will normally be a maximum of 3 directions, although in some cases this can be just 2.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/cancelled-or-stopped-tests-and-bad-weather","slug":"cancelled-or-stopped-tests-and-bad-weather","order":10,"title":"Cancelled or stopped tests and bad weather","body":"<p>Sometimes the Driving Standards Agency (<abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>) has to cancel or stop motorcycle practical tests because of bad weather, vehicle problems or other reasons.</p>\n\n<h2>Bad weather</h2>\n\n<p>Practical riding tests are not held in dangerous weather conditions, for example when the roads are icy.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If your test is cancelled because of bad weather, another will be arranged automatically at no further cost.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Only call your test centre if there is snow or ice in your local area on the day of your test.</p>\n\n<h2>When to phone your test centre</h2>\n\n<p>If your test is early in the morning, call as soon as you can on the day. If you call the day before, the test centre won&rsquo;t be able to tell you if your test will go ahead.</p>\n\n<p>If your test is in the afternoon, call the test centre later in the morning. The test centre is more likely to know if the roads will be suitable for your test.</p>\n\n<h3>If there&rsquo;s no answer from the test centre</h3>\n\n<p>If nobody answers the phone, and the conditions in your area aren&rsquo;t looking too bad, it&rsquo;s likely that the examiners are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>checking the local roads to see if practical tests can go ahead</li>\n  <li>taking tests because the conditions are suitable</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>However, this isn&rsquo;t a guarantee that your test will go ahead. Call the test centre again or go there in time for your test.</p>\n\n<h2>If your test can&rsquo;t go ahead</h2>\n\n<p>A new appointment date will usually be sent to you within 3 working days. This could take up to 7 days when the bad weather goes on for longer.</p>\n\n<p>You won’t be able to claim for any out-of-pocket expenses.</p>\n\n<h2>Waiting times for a practical test</h2>\n\n<p>As well as causing cancellations, bad weather can sometimes lead to longer waiting times for practical test appointments.</p>\n\n<h2>If your test is cancelled by <abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr> for other reasons</h2>\n\n<p>If your test is cancelled at short notice you might be able to claim out-of-pocket expenses.</p>\n\n<p>‘Short notice’ means less than 3 clear working days’ notice. Working days include Saturdays, but don’t include public holidays.</p>\n\n<p>You can’t claim if the test was cancelled because of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>bad weather and poor light</li>\n  <li>problems with your motorcycle</li>\n  <li>rider problems</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need to fill out and return a claim form to <abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/@motor/documents/digitalasset/dg_196447.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Application for refunding out-of-pocket expenses' (PDF, 176KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Application for refunding out-of-pocket expenses’ (PDF, 176KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"address\"><div class=\"adr org fn\"><p>\n\n\n<br /><abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>  \n<br />PO Box 280  \n<br />Newcastle-upon-Tyne  \n<br />NE99 1FP\n<br />\n<br />\n</p></div></div>\n\n<h2>Problems with you or your vehicle</h2>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll have to take another test at your own cost if your test can&rsquo;t be completed because of a problem with:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you - for example, if you feel unwell while taking your test</li>\n  <li>your motorcycle or moped - for example, if it breaks down during the test or is not suitable for the test</li>\n</ul>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/motorcycle-practical-test/practical-test-candidate-impersonation","slug":"practical-test-candidate-impersonation","order":11,"title":"Practical test candidate impersonation","body":"<p>It&rsquo;s illegal to impersonate someone (pretend to be them) and take the practical test for them.</p>\n\n<p>Impersonators and people who use their services have been convicted in the criminal courts and given prison sentences.</p>\n\n<p>The Driving Standards Agency (<abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>) investigates every case of suspected impersonation and works closely with the police to take offenders to court.</p>\n\n<h2>Report an impersonator</h2>\n\n<p>If someone offers to impersonate you for your practical test, report it to <abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong><abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr> integrity team</strong>  </p>\n\n<p><a href=\"&#109;&#097;&#105;&#108;&#116;&#111;:&#105;&#110;&#116;&#101;&#103;&#114;&#105;&#116;&#121;&#046;&#116;&#101;&#097;&#109;&#064;&#100;&#115;&#097;&#046;&#103;&#115;&#105;&#046;&#103;&#111;&#118;&#046;&#117;&#107;\">&#105;&#110;&#116;&#101;&#103;&#114;&#105;&#116;&#121;&#046;&#116;&#101;&#097;&#109;&#064;&#100;&#115;&#097;&#046;&#103;&#115;&#105;&#04